{"data":{"post":{"id":"9cb2bac8-53ba-55fc-acc0-f56ba4f02273","html":"<p>Welcome to my first blog, âœ¨ M0Nk3y WebDev<img class=\"emoji-icon\" data-icon=\"emoji-sparkles\" style=\"display: inline; margin: 0; margin-top: 1px; position: relative; top: 5px; width: 25px\" src=\"data:image/png;base64, \"> !! After witnessing tons of cool blogs written by other developers, learning all sorts of practical tips and gaining incredibly useful knowledge thru thoughtfully written tutorials, it was a no-brainer to me that someday Iâ€™d create one, aswell. Surprise, surprise that day is today ðŸ˜„ . I hope somebody learns something thatâ€™ll help them create their own web app and further their education towards software development!</p>\n<p>For my first post, Iâ€™ll show you how I created this blog,step by step. After trying multiple different frameworks, <a href=\"https://jekyllrb.com\">Jekyll</a> ðŸ˜‰ , <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/\">WordPress</a> ðŸ˜‰ , I finally landed on <a href=\"https://www.gatsbyjs.org/\">Gatsby.js</a>. Although both former frameworks worked well and provided everything necessary to create a nice blog, they werenâ€™t flexible enough for what I was after, especially after starting to use <a href=\"https://reactjs.org/\">React.js</a>, <a href=\"https://redux.js.org/\">Redux.js</a>, and <a href=\"https://vuejs.org/\">Vue.js</a>. <a href=\"https://www.gatsbyjs.org/\">Gatsbyâ€™s</a> true strength lies in itâ€™s component based architect, while mainting static site builds, hence compatability with <a href=\"https://pages.github.com/\" title=\"Github Pages Homepage\">Github Pages</a>ðŸ˜¼ , and other free repo web hosts. So, without further ado, hereâ€™s the steps I took to build this blog using the fantastic ðŸ›  <a href=\"https://www.gatsbyjs.org/\">gatsby.js</a>:</p>\n<h2>Installing gatsby-cli</h2>\n<ol>\n<li>First we use <a href=\"https://www.npmjs.com\">NPM</a> or <a href=\"https://yarnpkg.com/en/\">Yarn</a> to install <a href=\"https://www.gatsbyjs.org/docs/gatsby-cli/\">gatsby-cli</a>.</li>\n</ol>\n<blockquote>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.gatsbyjs.org/docs/gatsby-cli/\">Gatsby-cli</a> will be installed globally, meaning weâ€™ll be able to use this tool to install different starter sites anywhere we want ðŸ˜„</p>\n</blockquote>\n<h4>NPM:</h4>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"bash\"><pre class=\"language-bash\"><code class=\"language-bash\">$ <span class=\"token function\">npm</span> <span class=\"token function\">install</span> --global gatsby-cli</code></pre></div>\n<h4>Yarn:</h4>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"bash\"><pre class=\"language-bash\"><code class=\"language-bash\">$ yarn add gatsby-cli --global</code></pre></div>\n<ol start=\"2\">\n<li>\n<p>Now we use gatsby-cli to create a new project.</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>We need a dir to build our projects. Itâ€™s up to you where ever that is, I made mine ~/gatsby . After moving into our new dir we call up gatsby to create a new project. First weâ€™ll make their sample one, to see how to structure our site folders, etc.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"bash\"><pre class=\"language-bash\"><code class=\"language-bash\">$ <span class=\"token function\">mkdir</span> ~/gatsby\n$ <span class=\"token function\">cd</span> ~/gatsby\n$ gatsby new gatsby-site\n$ <span class=\"token function\">cd</span> gatsby-site\n$ <span class=\"token function\">ls</span> -lta</code></pre></div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Now we can use gatsby to serve our site <em>locally</em> and any changes me make to the files will be <em><strong>hot-loaded</strong> automatically</em> to our browser. Our site will be available at <em><strong>localhost:8000</strong></em>.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"bash\"><pre class=\"language-bash\"><code class=\"language-bash\">$ gatsby develop</code></pre></div>\n</li>\n</ol>","fields":{"slug":"/first-post-thanks-to-gatsby/","prefix":"2018-11-07"},"frontmatter":{"title":"